{
  "doc_id": "1128",
  "text": "REBOV was originally reported in wild-caught cynomolgus monkeys (Macaca fascicularis) imported from the Philippines into the United States [CITATION_1] , and has also been reported in pigs both in the Philippines [CITATION_2] ) and China [CITATION_3] as an infection concurrent with porcine reproductive and respiratory syndrome virus (PRRSV), so it was not clear if REBOV was causing any clinical signs. Marsh and colleagues did not observe clinical signs in pigs experimentally infected with REBOV [CITATION_4] . REBOV has not been shown to cause symptomatic infections in humans. The animal and public health implications of this EBOV species are yet to be determined.",
